container" class=3D"markdown"><p>Compiler fuzzing for small languages is a =
specific problem =E2=80=94 few optimization passes, tiny corpora, thin docs=
. This post covers how coverage-guided fuzzing and LLM-assisted tooling ada=
pt to smart-contract compilers, including a literature overview, related pr=
ojects, and evaluation results. Found <strong>100+ compiler bugs</strong> a=
cross <a href=3D"https://github.com/MystenLabs/sui/issues?q=3Dis%3Aissue%20=
author%3Ajubnzv" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Sui Move</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/issues?q=3Dis%3Aissue%=
20author%3Ajubnzv" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Cairo</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://github.com/hyperledger-solang/solang/issues?q=3Dis%3Ais=
sue%20author%3Ajubnzv" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Solang=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://github.com/argotorg/solidity/issues?q=3Dis%3Aissue=
%20author%3Ajubnzv" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Solidity<=
/a>, and <a href=3D"https://github.com/ProvableHQ/leo/issues?q=3Dis%3Aissue=
%20author%3Ajubnzv" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Leo</a>. =
These are not lexer or parser crashes on malformed input =E2=80=94 every bu=
g was triggered by structurally valid programs against mature, audited, pro=
duction compilers.</p>
<p>This post may be useful to you if you:</p>
<ul>
<li>Develop, maintain, or test a programming language, especially one targe=
ting smart contracts</li>
<li>Do structure-aware fuzzing against real-world targets</li>
</ul>
<p>The post is organized as follows:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#backg=
round">Background</a></strong> =E2=80=94 related work, existing approaches,=
 and what makes small-language fuzzing different from C/C++</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#fuzzi=
ng-harness-and-configuration">Fuzzing harness and configuration</a></strong=
> =E2=80=94 harness design, fuzzer orchestration, tuning for compiler targe=
ts</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#custo=
m-mutators">Custom mutators</a></strong> =E2=80=94 leveraging LLMs and tree=
-sitter grammars in AFL++ mutators</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#corpu=
s-and-dictionaries">Corpus and dictionaries</a></strong> =E2=80=94 corpus c=
ollection, minimization, dictionary construction</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#triag=
e-workflow">Triage workflow</a></strong> =E2=80=94 deduplication, minimizat=
ion assisted by tools and LLM, and report filing</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#evalu=
ation">Evaluation</a></strong> =E2=80=94 all targets, all results, consolid=
ated</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#concl=
usion-and-further-work">Conclusion and further work</a></strong> =E2=80=94 =
summarizes the post, notes what comes next, lists the published tools</li>
</ol>
<h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"background">Backgrou=
nd<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Background" title=3D"=
Direct link to Background" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-=
part-1#background">=E2=80=8B</a></h2>
<p>Fuzzing is one of the approaches for finding bugs in compilers. While it=
 does not provide correctness guarantees, it enables you to uncover hidden =
bugs by generating corner cases that users rarely trigger. Compilers are pa=
rticularly good targets =E2=80=93 they process complex structured input thr=
ough multiple transformation passes with internal invariants and assumption=
s.</p>
<p>In the simplest case, the goal is to find compiler crashes =E2=80=93 int=
ernal compiler errors (ICE). This is easy, because you don't have to write =
a fuzzing oracle =E2=80=93 just execute the compilation pipeline on fuzz da=
ta and collect crashes. This post focuses only on ICE; other kinds of error=
s will be covered in the later part.</p>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-valid-leo-crash-bfe7fda170a23b351190cbe685a6c2bd.png" style=3D"width: 75%=
;"></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em>Valid ICE: hex literal as array index =E2=86=92 c=
ompiler panic (<a href=3D"https://github.com/ProvableHQ/leo/issues/29229" t=
arget=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">leo#29229</a>)</em></div>
<br>
<p>The issues found that way have a low risk for end users =E2=80=93 these =
bugs may crash the tooling (e.g. analyzers, LSP) or the compiler itself, pr=
eventing the user from writing planned code and messing up the development =
process. They don't affect the running program.</p>
<p>The standard fuzzing technique when source code is available is coverage=
-guided fuzzing. Popular fuzzers operate at byte and bit level =E2=80=94 bu=
t compilers accept structured input. Pushing random bytes will only hit lex=
er/parser errors and is far too ineffective to reach later passes. That's w=
hy grammar-aware fuzzing exists.</p>
<p><strong>Key idea of grammar-aware fuzzing</strong>: generate syntactical=
ly correct programs that likely pass the lexer/parser and hit internals of =
the compiler. This way, we challenge later passes like the typechecker, sem=
antic analysis, and codegen =E2=80=93 trying to violate some invariants and=
 assumptions the compiler developers made.</p>
<p>While challenging the lexer/parser is easy, it was intentionally skipped=
 for all the compilers. In small teams and small languages, nobody really c=
ares if input containing 5000 sequential <code>(</code> symbols will crash =
the parser. This kind of issue is very common and could be easily found, bu=
t it is not worth the time to report or fix, because no sane user will ever=
 write code like this.</p>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-malformed-cairo-3df8dd061394436514a29be7f25dd1eb.png"></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em>Cairo: malformed AST (unterminated <code>$</code>=
 in macro rule) =E2=86=92 out-of-bounds access. Such bugs <strong>were not =
considered valid</strong> and <strong>not reported</strong>.</em></div>
<br>
<p>Most existing research on grammar-aware compiler fuzzing targets C/C++ c=
ompilers. Some of these approaches transfer to smart-contract languages, so=
me do not. Here is what makes these targets different:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Few optimization passes</strong> =E2=80=93 smart-contract langu=
ages focus on correctness, not runtime speed, and are developed by small te=
ams. Program generators (e.g. <a href=3D"https://github.com/csmith-project/=
csmith" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">CSmith</a> or <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/intel/yarpgen" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener nor=
eferrer">YARPGen</a>) or EMI mutators (like Hermes <a href=3D"https://nowar=
p.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#references">[7]</a> or XDead <a href=3D"h=
ttps://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#references">[8]</a>) that tar=
get miscompilations from aggressive optimizations are of limited use here.<=
/li>
<li><strong>Simpler execution environments</strong> =E2=80=93 smart-contrac=
t languages target smart-contracts, not general-purpose computing. This mea=
ns fewer codegen paths and a simpler runtime, which limits the surface for =
deep codegen bugs.</li>
<li><strong>Rust as implementation language</strong> =E2=80=93 many of thes=
e compilers are written in Rust, which determines the tooling (cargo-fuzz, =
AFL++ Rust bindings) and the crash patterns we target: panics, unprotected =
unwraps, index-out-of-bounds.</li>
<li><strong>Low popularity</strong> =E2=80=93 fewer real-world examples are=
 available, which limits corpus collection and approaches that rely on inje=
cting existing code snippets into the fuzzing process <a href=3D"https://no=
warp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#references">[1]</a>.</li>
<li><strong>Often poor documentation</strong> =E2=80=93 approaches leveragi=
ng language documentation or specification <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blo=
g/compiler-testing-part-1#references">[3]</a> are limited, though they work=
 when teams explicitly care about good docs.</li>
<li><strong>Tree-sitter grammars available</strong> =E2=80=93 smart-contrac=
t languages typically ship <a href=3D"https://tree-sitter.github.io/" targe=
t=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">tree-sitter</a> grammars for tooli=
ng (IDE extensions, syntax highlighting), while <a href=3D"https://www.antl=
r.org/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">ANTLR4</a> grammars a=
re rare. This makes tools leveraging tree-sitter work well out of the box.<=
/li>
</ul>
<p>The fuzzing campaign for ICE requires the following parts to be implemen=
ted:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#fuzzi=
ng-harness-and-configuration">Fuzzing harness</a></strong> =E2=80=93 execut=
es the compilation pipeline on fuzz inputs and collects crashes. Needed to =
run fuzzers in persistent mode and filter out benign panics like stack over=
flows from parser bugs.</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#custo=
m-mutators">Custom mutators</a></strong> =E2=80=93 implement grammar-aware =
mutation rules on top of AFL++. Default byte-level mutators can't generate =
structurally valid programs, so custom mutators are what actually get past =
the parser.</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#corpu=
s-and-dictionaries">Corpus</a></strong> =E2=80=93 a collection of seed prog=
rams that mutations are derived from. All grammar-aware mutators operate on=
 these inputs, so corpus quality directly determines mutation quality.</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#dicti=
onaries">Fuzzing dictionaries</a></strong> =E2=80=93 lists of language-spec=
ific tokens fed to default mutators (if used). Help byte-level mutations pr=
oduce valid-looking fragments instead of pure noise.</li>
</ul>
<h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"fuzzing-harness-and-=
configuration">Fuzzing harness and configuration<a class=3D"hash-link" aria=
-label=3D"Direct link to Fuzzing harness and configuration" title=3D"Direct=
 link to Fuzzing harness and configuration" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/=
compiler-testing-part-1#fuzzing-harness-and-configuration">=E2=80=8B</a></h=
2>
<p>A fuzzing harness is a program that sets up fuzzers in persistent mode t=
o receive and process fuzz inputs looking for crashes. Additionally, it sor=
ts out benign panics, like stack overflows typically caused by lexer/parser=
 bugs.</p>
<p>The main fuzzer used is AFL++. It is the most mature, provides an API to=
 write custom mutators, and has the best configuration options. Meanwhile, =
honggfuzz and libFuzzer use different mutation algorithms, which increases =
coverage when combined with AFL++.</p>
<p>In some campaigns, honggfuzz and libFuzzer were executed in a single thr=
ead and were supplementary; the main work was done by AFL++.</p>
<p>While AFL++ <a href=3D"https://github.com/AFLplusplus/AFLplusplus//blob/=
4e5c0469ad9d56060317ebdc88027e2143f7b979/docs/Changelog.md#L931" target=3D"=
_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">provides an option</a> to sync with for=
eign fuzzers, you'll still need to implement different harness binaries for=
 each fuzzer.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"multifuzz-unified-or=
chestration"><code>multifuzz</code>: unified orchestration<a class=3D"hash-=
link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to multifuzz-unified-orchestration" title=
=3D"Direct link to multifuzz-unified-orchestration" href=3D"https://nowarp.=
io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#multifuzz-unified-orchestration">=E2=80=8B<=
/a></h3>
<p>To simplify configuration and orchestration of multiple fuzzers, a light=
weight orchestrator called <a href=3D"https://github.com/jubnzv/multifuzz" =
target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer"><code>multifuzz</code></a> wa=
s implemented. It solves three tasks:</p>
<ul>
<li>Unified Rust API to configure all three fuzzers in a single config</li>
<li>Explicit configuration for all the fuzzers =E2=80=93 all <a href=3D"htt=
ps://aflplus.plus/docs/env_variables/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener no=
referrer">env variables</a> and fuzzer arguments must be described explicit=
ly in the config, zero hidden options</li>
<li>CLI to manage individual fuzzing instances: start, stop, restart</li>
</ul>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-multifuzz-harness-842c942f7cb610d44080e6fe8b05dcc2.png"></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em>multifuzz harness: single Rust macro shared by AF=
L++, honggfuzz, and libFuzzer</em></div>
<br>
<p>Overall, it adds a zero-overhead configuration layer that sets up a sing=
le harness for all three fuzzers and manages them at runtime. Everything is=
 100% explicit =E2=80=93 the tool does not introduce any fancy defaults, so=
 you have to <a href=3D"https://aflplus.plus/docs/fuzzing_in_depth/" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">read the documentation</a>.</p>
<p>Here is an <a href=3D"https://github.com/nowarp/move-fuzz/blob/f59321cb2=
99c4877d64493d4c0a95d2f54f5f7bc/crates/source-multifuzz/multifuzz.toml" tar=
get=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">example configuration</a> used t=
o fuzz the Sui Move compiler that shows how multiple workers with different=
 options may be configured.</p>
<p>It is optional. Alternatively, you could achieve the same results writin=
g a Makefile or custom scripts and/or running <a href=3D"https://github.com=
/tmux/tmux/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">tmux</a> session=
s for each fuzzer worker.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"fuzzers-configuratio=
n">Fuzzers configuration<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to=
 Fuzzers configuration" title=3D"Direct link to Fuzzers configuration" href=
=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#fuzzers-configuration">=
=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>To achieve the best fuzzer performance for grammar-aware testing, the fo=
llowing options were used:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Selective instrumentation</strong> =E2=80=93 used to focus fuzz=
ing on specific places in the source code, like recently added features in =
the compiler. The approach used AFL++ partial instrumentation and is well d=
escribed in <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#refer=
ences">[2]</a> and the <a href=3D"https://github.com/AFLplusplus/AFLplusplu=
s/blob/stable/instrumentation/README.instrument_list.md" target=3D"_blank" =
rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">documentation</a>.</li>
<li><strong>No complex byte level mutators</strong> were used =E2=80=93 cmp=
-log (or redqueen <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1=
#references">[6]</a>), fuzzers <a href=3D"https://github.com/microsvuln/awe=
some-afl" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">involving symbolic =
execution</a>, and <a href=3D"https://github.com/AngoraFuzzer/Angora" targe=
t=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Angora</a> (which uses taint trace=
s from inputs) were all skipped, since they were designed to target bit/byt=
e-level mutations. For grammar-aware fuzzing this does not give much benefi=
t, and considering the execution overhead, it slows down the fuzzer.</li>
<li><strong>Timeouts</strong> =E2=80=93 compilers are slow, and some mutati=
ons may generate code that increases compilation time, e.g. by hitting cons=
tant evaluation or generating many entries. The timeout was typically set a=
round 1000ms =E2=80=93 enough to keep the corpus clean and avoid cluttering=
 it with useless inputs.</li>
<li><strong>Memory limits</strong> =E2=80=93 some targets eat RAM; a specia=
l case is Cairo, which uses <a href=3D"https://github.com/salsa-rs/salsa" t=
arget=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Salsa</a> =E2=80=93 an increme=
ntal computation library with its own cache. Other projects may also consum=
e a lot of memory when dealing with large generated inputs. The <code>-m</c=
ode> option is required.</li>
</ul>
<p>Otherwise, the fuzzing process relies mostly on custom mutators. Fuzzer =
configuration follows the <a href=3D"https://aflplus.plus/docs/fuzzing_in_d=
epth/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">AFL++ documentation</a=
>.</p>
<h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"custom-mutators">Cus=
tom mutators<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Custom muta=
tors" title=3D"Direct link to Custom mutators" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/bl=
og/compiler-testing-part-1#custom-mutators">=E2=80=8B</a></h2>
<p>Recent versions of AFL++ provide <a href=3D"https://github.com/AFLpluspl=
us/AFLplusplus/blob/4e5c0469ad9d56060317ebdc88027e2143f7b979/custom_mutator=
s/rust/README.md" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Rust API bi=
ndings</a> to write custom mutators, which simplify development =E2=80=94 s=
mart-contract languages are often written in Rust, so you can trigger their=
 internals (e.g. parser, AST) directly from the custom mutator.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"ad-hoc-custom-mutato=
r">Ad-hoc custom mutator<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to=
 Ad-hoc custom mutator" title=3D"Direct link to Ad-hoc custom mutator" href=
=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#ad-hoc-custom-mutator">=
=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>The first attempt was simple: after reading the <a href=3D"https://githu=
b.com/agroce/afl-compiler-fuzzer" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener norefer=
rer">experiment</a> conducted by Alex Groce <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/bl=
og/compiler-testing-part-1#references">[13]</a>, the idea was to create a M=
ove-specific AFL++ custom mutator. The result is a <a href=3D"https://githu=
b.com/nowarp/move-fuzz/tree/f59321cb299c4877d64493d4c0a95d2f54f5f7bc/custom=
_mutators/move" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">small mutator=
</a> written in C that swaps common language symbols (e.g. <code>{</code> a=
nd <code>[</code>), replaces and deletes code blocks, and provides some Mov=
e-specific mutations. It uses the custom mutator API and does not fork AFL+=
+.</p>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-move-mutator-cab49c7323cd37cc2ca5044633ee5768.png" style=3D"width: 75%;">=
</div>
<div align=3D"center"><em>Example of ad-hoc Move-specific mutations impleme=
nted</em></div>
<br>
<p>The problems with this approach:</p>
<ol>
<li>To be generic enough to target all C-style-syntax compilers, it has to =
sacrifice language-specific patterns</li>
<li>It relies heavily on a good corpus</li>
<li>It is too focused on havoc-style mutations without respecting program s=
tructure</li>
</ol>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"afl-ts-tree-sitter-b=
ased-afl-mutator"><code>afl-ts</code>: Tree-sitter based AFL++ mutator<a cl=
ass=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to afl-ts-tree-sitter-based-afl=
-mutator" title=3D"Direct link to afl-ts-tree-sitter-based-afl-mutator" hre=
f=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#afl-ts-tree-sitter-base=
d-afl-mutator">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>Instead of mutating bytes, we could mutate the AST directly. <a href=3D"=
https://tree-sitter.github.io/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferre=
r">Tree-sitter</a> grammars give you typed nodes to swap, delete, and splic=
e =E2=80=94 preserving program structure.</p>
<p>A similar tool and approach already exist in the Rust ecosystem: <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/langston-barrett/tree-splicer" target=3D"_blank" rel=
=3D"noopener noreferrer">tree-splicer</a> is used by <a href=3D"https://git=
hub.com/langston-barrett/tree-crasher" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener no=
referrer">tree-crasher</a> and <a href=3D"https://github.com/matthiaskrgr/i=
cemaker" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">ice-maker</a> to fin=
d ICEs in the rustc compiler. Similar mutation algorithms are applied in mu=
ltiple <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#other-gram=
mar-aware-fuzzers">grammar-aware fuzzing projects</a>, which typically use =
<a href=3D"https://www.antlr.org/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener norefe=
rrer">ANTLR4</a> grammars, uncommon among smart-contract languages. However=
, tree-splicer is a standalone tool, not an AFL++ custom mutator.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://github.com/jubnzv/afl-ts" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"no=
opener noreferrer"><code>afl-ts</code></a> mutator integrates grammar-aware=
 mutations into AFL++ as a custom mutator. It is fully configurable via env=
ironment variables and works with any tree-sitter grammar built with modern=
 tree-sitter. Instead of tweaking the mutator to add the language <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/langston-barrett/tree-splicer/pull/3/changes#diff-0a=
ef08b59d5e277120a6ed6f290f2171683340f202fb8aaf745cb0f4a1d4e7bdR4" target=3D=
"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">as needed in tree-splicer</a>, the use=
r just points to the grammar shared library via the <code>TS_GRAMMAR</code>=
 env variable; the language function name can be set via <code>TS_LANG_FUNC=
</code>, but the tool can usually deduce it from the grammar filename.</p>
<p>Here is the complete table of mutations it conducts:</p>
<table><thead><tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Weight</th><th>What it does</th></tr=
></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>ts-del</code></td><td>20</td><td>Delete a nam=
ed AST subtree</td></tr><tr><td><code>ts-bank</code></td><td>20</td><td>Rep=
lace subtree with type-compatible one from corpus bank (<code>TSSymbol</cod=
e> match)</td></tr><tr><td><code>ts-add</code></td><td>20</td><td>Replace s=
ubtree with type-compatible one from AFL++'s <code>add_buf</code></td></tr>=
<tr><td><code>ts-swap</code></td><td>15</td><td>Swap two sibling nodes of t=
he same type</td></tr><tr><td><code>ts-shrink</code></td><td>10</td><td>Rep=
lace node with a same-type descendant (always reduces size)</td></tr><tr><t=
d><code>ts-lit</code></td><td>5</td><td>Replace leaf with random literal</t=
d></tr><tr><td><code>ts-dup</code></td><td>3</td><td>Duplicate a subtree ad=
jacent to itself</td></tr><tr><td><code>ts-ins</code></td><td>7</td><td>Ins=
ert a type-compatible bank subtree after a node (grows input, capped at 2x)=
</td></tr><tr><td><code>ts-range</code></td><td>4</td><td>Replace a contigu=
ous run of same-symbol siblings with a same-symbol run from <code>add_buf</=
code> or 1..3 concatenated bank entries</td></tr><tr><td><code>ts-chaos</co=
de></td><td>2</td><td>Bypass the type-safety filter on <code>ts-bank</code>=
 / <code>ts-add</code> / <code>ts-range</code> / <code>ts-kins</code> / <co=
de>ts-stutter</code>: splice a random bank (or <code>add_buf</code>) node i=
nto the destination regardless of <code>TSSymbol</code>, or stutter the env=
elope of any parent around any descendant. Produces deliberately ungrammati=
cal inputs to increase coverage.</td></tr><tr><td><code>ts-kdel</code></td>=
<td>10</td><td>Delete 1..3 contiguous children from a run of same-symbol si=
blings, swallowing one adjacent separator so the remaining list stays well-=
formed</td></tr><tr><td><code>ts-kins</code></td><td>10</td><td>Insert 1..3=
 same-symbol children at a random boundary of a same-symbol sibling run. Do=
nors come from <code>add_buf</code>, the bank, or a duplicated existing mem=
ber. Separator is detected from the existing list</td></tr><tr><td><code>ts=
-stutter</code></td><td>4</td><td>Pick a parent <code>P</code> and a same-s=
ymbol descendant <code>C</code>, then repeat <code>P</code>'s prefix/suffix=
 envelope <code>N</code> times around <code>C</code> (<a href=3D"https://gi=
tlab.com/akihe/radamsa" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">radam=
sa</a>-style tree stutter). Type-safe by default; chaos mode drops the symb=
ol-equality filter.</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Weights represent the probability of each mutation being applied.</p>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-ts-add-1d52b933e8f77ec740007850cfefff17.png"></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em><code>ts-add</code> replaces a function element's=
 contents with another from the same file. <code>ts-bank</code> does the sa=
me across files in the queue.</em></div>
<br>
<p>Typically, corpus files grow a little when using <code>ts-ins</code> a l=
ot, but not significantly, because the addition must add some coverage to b=
e kept by AFL++.</p>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-ts-swap-6a6b5e8a819b9a4401d7cb388aac9641.png"></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em><code>ts-swap</code> picks matching elements (her=
e, function return types) and swaps them.</em></div>
<br>
<p>This mutator alone found lots of bugs; most of the <a href=3D"https://gi=
thub.com/hyperledger-solang/solang/issues?q=3Dis%3Aissue%20author%3Ajubnzv"=
 target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Solang</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://github.com/argotorg/solidity/issues?q=3Dis%3Aissue%20author%3Ajubnzv"=
 target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Solidity</a> findings came f=
rom it.</p>
<p>The quality of the tree-sitter grammar matters =E2=80=94 grammars produc=
ing too many <code>ERROR</code> nodes on valid input degrade mutation quali=
ty. Here are the grammars used:</p>
<table><thead><tr><th>Target</th><th>Tree-sitter grammar</th></tr></thead><=
tbody><tr><td>Sui Move</td><td><a href=3D"https://github.com/MystenLabs/sui=
/tree/main/external-crates/move/tooling/tree-sitter" target=3D"_blank" rel=
=3D"noopener noreferrer">tree-sitter-move</a></td></tr><tr><td>Cairo</td><t=
d><a href=3D"https://github.com/starkware-libs/tree-sitter-cairo" target=3D=
"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">tree-sitter-cairo</a></td></tr><tr><td=
>Leo</td><td><a href=3D"https://github.com/r001/tree-sitter-leo" target=3D"=
_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">tree-sitter-leo</a></td></tr><tr><td>So=
lidity / Solang</td><td><a href=3D"https://github.com/JoranHonig/tree-sitte=
r-solidity" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">tree-sitter-solid=
ity</a></td></tr></tbody></table>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"metamut-style-mutato=
rs">MetaMut-style mutators<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link =
to MetaMut-style mutators" title=3D"Direct link to MetaMut-style mutators" =
href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#metamut-style-mutato=
rs">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>Beyond tree-sitter mutations, we want language-specific operations that =
test semantic and codegen passes =E2=80=94 without hand-writing them. MetaM=
ut solves this.</p>
<p>The MetaMut paper <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-par=
t-1#references">[5]</a> describes an approach to generating language-specif=
ic mutations using LLMs. While the experiment in the paper <a href=3D"https=
://github.com/icsnju/MetaMut" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer"=
>focused</a> on C and C++ compilers, it can be applied to Rust-based smart-=
contract languages as well.</p>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-metamut-scheme-5eceb27d01540ba7678430781c2ad8d7.png"></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em>MetaMut pipeline (source: <a href=3D"https://conn=
glli.github.io/pdfs/metamut_asplos24.pdf" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener=
 noreferrer">original paper</a>)</em></div>
<br>
<p>We will consider the MetaMut-style mutator developed for Sui Move: <a hr=
ef=3D"https://github.com/nowarp/move-fuzz/tree/f59321cb299c4877d64493d4c0a9=
5d2f54f5f7bc/custom_mutators/metamove" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener no=
referrer">MetaMove</a>. While the approach is applicable to other languages=
, we will focus on Move, which contains <a href=3D"https://github.com/nowar=
p/move-fuzz/tree/f59321cb299c4877d64493d4c0a95d2f54f5f7bc/custom_mutators/m=
etamove/src/mutators" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">884 uni=
que mutators</a> plus all the <a href=3D"https://github.com/nowarp/move-fuz=
z/tree/f59321cb299c4877d64493d4c0a95d2f54f5f7bc/custom_mutators/metamove/sc=
ripts" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">scripts</a> needed to =
demonstrate the approach. While the core idea is similar to MetaMut, the im=
plementation differs in several ways.</p>
<p>From the implementation perspective, it consists of these components:</p=
>
<ol>
<li><strong>Rust mutator library</strong> =E2=80=93 a small Rust library th=
at lets the model create custom mutators using the compiler's AST without r=
eading the whole compiler codebase on each step. It contains a simplified A=
ST and some logic to call custom mutators.</li>
<li><strong>Script to invent new mutators</strong> =E2=80=93 combines mutat=
ing operations (<code>swap</code>, <code>toggle</code>, ...) with all avail=
able AST elements, generates descriptions of how each mutation should work,=
 and saves the results.</li>
<li><strong>Script to implement new mutators</strong> =E2=80=93 takes the d=
escriptions generated by the previous script and the AST from the library, =
and calls the model to generate mutations with compilation feedback.</li>
<li><strong>Script to verify the generated mutators</strong> =E2=80=93 chec=
ks whether all of them can be applied and whether they generate syntactical=
ly valid code.</li>
</ol>
<p>The experiment used <strong>Sonnet 4.6</strong> to invent and generate t=
he mutators.</p>
<p>Consider the implementation and differences from the original approach i=
n greater detail.</p>
<h4 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"rust-mutator-library=
">Rust mutator library<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to R=
ust mutator library" title=3D"Direct link to Rust mutator library" href=3D"=
https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#rust-mutator-library">=E2=80=
=8B</a></h4>
<p>The library wraps the Move parser, walks the AST, collecting target cate=
gories (expressions, if/match/loop, let bindings, function calls, etc.), an=
d exposes a single <code>MuAstContext</code> that each mutator operates on.=
 Each generated mutator implements a <code>MoveMutator</code> trait with fo=
ur methods: <code>name()</code>, <code>description()</code>, <code>needs()<=
/code> returning a bitmask of required AST targets, and <code>mutate()</cod=
e> that edits the source via byte-offset rewriting =E2=80=94 no AST-to-sour=
ce serializer needed.</p>
<p>Pre-filtering by <code>needs()</code> is the key efficiency trick: the f=
uzz loop computes the available target kinds once per input, and only mutat=
ors whose <code>needs()</code> overlap with those kinds get invoked. A mini=
mal example:</p>
