<h4 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"validating-mutators"=
>Validating mutators<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Val=
idating mutators" title=3D"Direct link to Validating mutators" href=3D"http=
s://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#validating-mutators">=E2=80=8B</=
a></h4>
<p>The implement phase only guarantees compilation =E2=80=94 not useful beh=
avior. The <a href=3D"https://github.com/nowarp/move-fuzz/blob/f59321cb299c=
4877d64493d4c0a95d2f54f5f7bc/custom_mutators/metamove/scripts/validate_synt=
ax.py" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">validation script</a> =
runs each registered mutator against clean source files from the corpus and=
 classifies the output via <code>move-check</code>:</p>
<ol>
<li>Sample N compilable files from the corpus (no parser/lexer errors in ba=
seline)</li>
<li>Apply each mutator to K files with different seeds (parallel workers)</=
li>
<li>Classify resulting errors by <code>move-check</code> category:
<ul>
<li><strong>category 1</strong> (parser/lexer) =E2=86=92 invalid syntax, mu=
tator <strong>rejected</strong></li>
<li><strong>categories 2-4</strong> (name resolution, unbound variables, ty=
pe errors) =E2=86=92 acceptable, these are exactly the passes we want to te=
st</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Flag mutators that never apply (always no-op, wasting CPU) =E2=80=94 an=
 example: a generated top-level-declaration mutator that looked for <code>u=
se</code> among function statements</li>
</ol>
<p>The script also highlights gaps in the corpus =E2=80=93 if a mutation ne=
ver applies, the needed construction is likely missing from the corpus.</p>
<h4 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"conclusion">Conclusi=
on<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Conclusion" title=3D"=
Direct link to Conclusion" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-=
part-1#conclusion">=E2=80=8B</a></h4>
<p>Having hundreds of LLM-generated mutators challenging semantic and codeg=
en passes <em>almost for free</em> is a big win for compiler fuzzing =E2=80=
=94 it opens new paths and increases coverage without hand-writing a progra=
m generator or spending time on custom coverage-guided tooling.</p>
<p>It works best when combined with other grammar-aware mutators like the <=
a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#afl-ts-tree-sitter=
-based-afl-mutator">tree-sitter splice mutator</a>, which adds randomness a=
nd uncovers more subtle cases.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"built-in-afl-mutator=
s">Built-in AFL++ mutators<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link =
to Built-in AFL++ mutators" title=3D"Direct link to Built-in AFL++ mutators=
" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#built-in-afl-mutat=
ors">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>AFL++ ships with several <a href=3D"https://github.com/AFLplusplus/AFLpl=
usplus/tree/stable/custom_mutators" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noref=
errer">custom mutators</a> in its distribution. Multiple mutators can be st=
acked via <code>AFL_CUSTOM_MUTATOR_LIBRARY</code> =E2=80=94 different mutat=
ion algorithms hit different paths, so combining a grammar-aware mutators w=
ith byte-level alternatives increases overall coverage.</p>
<h4 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"autotokens">autotoke=
ns<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to autotokens" title=3D"=
Direct link to autotokens" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-=
part-1#autotokens">=E2=80=8B</a></h4>
<p>A grammar-free token fuzzer that splits input into tokens and shuffles t=
hem with different strategies. It learns its token pool from the <code>-x</=
code> dictionary and <code>CMPLOG</code>, and mutates below the grammar lev=
el. Useful as a lightweight complement to <code>afl-ts</code> =E2=80=94 it =
picks up on tokens the grammar-aware mutator does not know (e.g. identifier=
s present in the corpus but not captured in the AST).</p>
<h4 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"radamsa">radamsa<a c=
lass=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to radamsa" title=3D"Direct li=
nk to radamsa" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#radam=
sa">=E2=80=8B</a></h4>
<p><a href=3D"https://gitlab.com/akihe/radamsa" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"no=
opener noreferrer">radamsa</a> is a general-purpose byte-level fuzzer with =
several strategies that transfer to compiler fuzzing:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>sed-tree-stutter</code> =E2=80=94 generates deeply nested express=
ions (e.g. <code>f(g(h(f(g(h(f(g(h(x))))))))))</code>), often crashing pars=
er stack depth and occasionally triggering typechecker errors. <a href=3D"h=
ttps://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#afl-ts-tree-sitter-based-afl-=
mutator"><code>afl-ts</code></a> implements the same strategy at the gramma=
r level; radamsa operates at byte level and is more aggressive.</li>
<li><code>rand-as-count</code> =E2=80=94 appends large <code>A</code>-strin=
gs, useful for hitting integral-type boundaries and array length checks</li=
>
<li>Byte-level glyph injection =E2=80=94 adds "interesting" symbols (unicod=
e glyphs, control bytes) that crash the lexer/parser. Lexer/parser bugs are=
 <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#background">out =
of scope</a> here, but the strategy may be useful if you target them.</li>
<li>Boundary literal injection =E2=80=94 swaps numeric values with edge cas=
es (0, MAX, negative, large numbers) to stress integer overflow paths. <a h=
ref=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#afl-ts-tree-sitter-ba=
sed-afl-mutator"><code>afl-ts</code></a>'s <code>ts-lit</code> already does=
 this at the grammar level.</li>
</ul>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-radamsa-output-61ea764518a77912030ba094802ae907.png"></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em>radamsa introduced a large literal reproducing <a=
 href=3D"https://github.com/argotorg/solidity/issues/16619" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">solidity#16619</a></em></div>
<br>
<p>Caveats:</p>
<ul>
<li>Most radamsa output is parser/lexer noise that should be filtered durin=
g triage</li>
<li>Very large inputs slow the harness (e.g. constant evaluation on huge nu=
mbers)</li>
</ul>
<p>Not the primary mutator, but running it on one worker adds corpus divers=
ity.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"other-grammar-aware-=
fuzzers">Other grammar-aware fuzzers<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Di=
rect link to Other grammar-aware fuzzers" title=3D"Direct link to Other gra=
mmar-aware fuzzers" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#=
other-grammar-aware-fuzzers">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>There are other open-source fuzzers and custom mutators that may be used=
 to improve the fuzzing campaign. Some of them are integrated to AFL++ whil=
e some could be used as an external fuzzers (AFL++ <code>-F</code> flag).</=
p>
<p>Some fuzzers from papers and open-source projects represent ideas that o=
verlap with the approaches used here. They are mentioned because they may b=
e useful if you are writing your own tooling, or they may be more suitable =
for the language you are targeting:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/atnwalk/atnwalk" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D=
"noopener noreferrer">ATNwalk</a> =E2=80=93 provides grammar-aware mutation=
s and has <a href=3D"https://github.com/AFLplusplus/AFLplusplus//blob/4e5c0=
469ad9d56060317ebdc88027e2143f7b979/custom_mutators/atnwalk/README.md" targ=
et=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">built-in AFL++ integration</a>, b=
ut is not convenient to use since it requires a quality ANTLR4 grammar.</li=
>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/HexHive/Gramatron" target=3D"_blank" rel=
=3D"noopener noreferrer">Gramatron</a> =E2=80=93 grammar-aware fuzzer that =
operates on grammar automata, which was used for fuzzing an experimental la=
nguage for the <a href=3D"https://ton.org/en" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noop=
ener noreferrer">TON</a> blockchain; the main issue was the automaton gener=
ation algorithm. Grammars can be generated using <a href=3D"https://github.=
com/jubnzv/treesitter-to-gramatron" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noref=
errer">this script</a> or manually, but they must be very minimal. This is =
acceptable for dynamically typed languages like JavaScript as described in =
the paper <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#referen=
ces">[9]</a>, but for statically typed blockchain languages the grammars bl=
ow up the fixpoint algorithm that generates the automaton.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/fuzz4all/fuzz4all" target=3D"_blank" rel=
=3D"noopener noreferrer">Fuzz4All</a> =E2=80=93 uses LLM-based generation t=
o fuzz compilers <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#=
references">[12]</a>. A good option to <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/co=
mpiler-testing-part-1#corpus-and-dictionaries">extend the corpus</a> or run=
 separately alongside the coverage-guided fuzzer.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/uw-pluverse/perses/tree/master/kitten" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Kitten</a> =E2=80=93 an ANTLR4-=
based program generator that recently found 328 bugs in common compilers. I=
t uses grammar-aware mutations similar to tree-splicer or <code>afl-ts</cod=
e>, with additional strategies like rarity-weighted target selection, kleen=
e-targeted mutations, and top-down grammar generation powered by ANTLR4 <a =
href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#references">[10]</a>=
.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/ncsu-swat/IssueMut" target=3D"_blank" rel=
=3D"noopener noreferrer">IssueMut</a> =E2=80=93 the same idea as MetaMut, b=
ut previous findings are used as a source of mutations <a href=3D"https://n=
owarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#references">[11]</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>These are interesting sources of related mutation strategies that may be=
 used to improve the tooling.</p>
<h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"corpus-and-dictionar=
ies">Corpus and dictionaries<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct lin=
k to Corpus and dictionaries" title=3D"Direct link to Corpus and dictionari=
es" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#corpus-and-dicti=
onaries">=E2=80=8B</a></h2>
<p>The corpus feeds the mutators. Grammar-aware mutators like <a href=3D"ht=
tps://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#afl-ts-tree-sitter-based-afl-m=
utator"><code>afl-ts</code></a> and <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compi=
ler-testing-part-1#metamut-style-mutators">MetaMut-style</a> splice, swap, =
and delete subtrees from corpus entries. Byte-level mutators like radamsa a=
nd autotokens extract tokens from the same files. Corpus quality directly d=
etermines mutation quality =E2=80=94 mutators can only produce what they ca=
n see.</p>
<p>A good corpus is small, diverse, and covers a broad surface of the langu=
age. Small because havoc and custom splice-style mutators run faster on sma=
ll files, and oversized entries slow the whole campaign. Diverse because gr=
ammar-aware mutators only splice what's present in the corpus =E2=80=94 mis=
sing language constructs stay unreachable. The tension between "small" and =
"diverse" is resolved by minimization: collect broadly, then trim to the sm=
allest set that still covers the same paths (discussed in the next subsecti=
on).</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"collecting-corpus-fi=
les">Collecting corpus files<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct lin=
k to Collecting corpus files" title=3D"Direct link to Collecting corpus fil=
es" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#collecting-corpu=
s-files">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>The most straightforward way to seed the corpus is to collect source fil=
es somehwere, remove large and slow inputs and <a href=3D"https://aflplus.p=
lus/docs/fuzzing_in_depth/#b-making-the-input-corpus-unique" target=3D"_bla=
nk" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">minimize</a> the corpus.</p>
<p>To collect the initial corpus you could start with:</p>
<ul>
<li>compiler's test suite and examples</li>
<li>projects on GitHub</li>
<li>datasets, e.g. verifier/scan projects often provides information, there=
 are decompiled <a href=3D"https://github.com/MystenLabs/sui-packages/" tar=
get=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer"><code>sui-packages</code></a> fo=
r Sui Move or <a href=3D"https://huggingface.co/datasets/Zellic/all-ethereu=
m-contracts" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Zellic dataset o=
f Ethereum contracts</a></li>
</ul>
<p>The initial metric to evaluate the corpus coverage is <a href=3D"https:/=
/afl-1.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user_guide.html#map-coverage" target=3D"_bl=
ank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">AFL++ stats</a> and code coverage you coul=
d get with <code>llvm-cov</code>/<code>gcov</code>.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"tsgen-tree-sitter-ba=
sed-generation"><code>tsgen</code>: tree-sitter-based generation<a class=3D=
"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to tsgen-tree-sitter-based-generation=
" title=3D"Direct link to tsgen-tree-sitter-based-generation" href=3D"https=
://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#tsgen-tree-sitter-based-generatio=
n">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>Sometimes you get low coverage even after seeding with existing open-sou=
rce code for the compiler. This happens when the language is powerful enoug=
h that not all of its features are actively used, or when new features have=
 just been introduced.</p>
<p>This was the case for Cairo fuzzing. To cover the gaps, a small utility =
was created: <a href=3D"https://github.com/jubnzv/tsgen" target=3D"_blank" =
rel=3D"noopener noreferrer"><code>tsgen</code></a>.</p>
<p>It generates a seed corpus directly from a tree-sitter <code>grammar.jso=
n</code>. The generator walks the grammar recursively =E2=80=94 at each <co=
de>CHOICE</code> node it picks an alternative, at each <code>REPEAT</code> =
it picks a count, and at each terminal it samples from a dictionary (option=
ally augmented by identifiers and literals harvested from real source files=
). A min-depth pre-pass prevents infinite recursion through self-referentia=
l rules (<code>expression =E2=86=92 binary_op =E2=86=92 expression =E2=86=
=92 ...</code>), and generated programs are validated with the compiled par=
ser to drop anything that doesn't parse.</p>
<p>After generating the corpus, run <code>afl-cmin</code> on it. Practical =
results: 150k generated Solidity files reduced to ~1300 unique seeds under =
1024 bytes each; for the Cairo grammar it was ~700 seeds. That's a lot of s=
eeds for free =E2=80=94 the process takes less time than exploring the corp=
us from the ground up with grammar-aware mutators, and harvesting identifie=
rs from real source files gives better diversity.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"llm-based-seed-gener=
ation-with-coverage-feedback">LLM-based seed generation with coverage feedb=
ack<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to LLM-based seed gener=
ation with coverage feedback" title=3D"Direct link to LLM-based seed genera=
tion with coverage feedback" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testin=
g-part-1#llm-based-seed-generation-with-coverage-feedback">=E2=80=8B</a></h=
3>
<p>Another option: generate seeds with an LLM.</p>
<p>Obvious starting points:</p>
<ul>
<li>Explore previous findings for the repo and ask the LLM to generate seed=
s based on them.</li>
<li>Explore typically bug-prone code based on experience =E2=80=94 optimiza=
tions, code generation, IR transformations =E2=80=94 and ask the LLM to gen=
erate code that triggers specific places: constant folding, pattern matchin=
g compilation, etc.</li>
<li>Explore documentation and specification; generate seeds targeting rarel=
y-used or tricky constructions.</li>
<li>Use <code>git blame</code> on reachable code paths to generate seeds ta=
rgeting recently introduced changes.</li>
</ul>
<p>This works well when you are just starting the campaign and seeding the =
corpus. After that, its usefulness is limited, because grammar-aware fuzzer=
s will hit most of the paths anyway.</p>
<p>To avoid wasting time and tokens on already-covered paths, involve code =
coverage: look at which paths are not yet triggered and write a simple scri=
pt that asks the LLM to generate seeds for specific gaps, then check covera=
ge again in a feedback loop.</p>
<p>While code coverage <a href=3D"https://danielhall.io/code-coverage-is-a-=
terrible-metric" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">is not a goo=
d metric</a>, it at least lets you make sure your corpus doesn't have compl=
ete gaps.</p>
<p>Additionally, approaches like <a href=3D"https://github.com/ise-uiuc/Whi=
teFox" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">WhiteFox</a><a href=3D=
"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#references">[3]</a> that le=
verage language documentation for fuzzing were <a href=3D"https://gusarich.=
com/blog/fuzzing-with-llms" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">s=
uccessfully applied for TON</a>. But this requires good documentation and d=
oes not scale well when testing multiple compilers.</p>
<p>Another idea that worked: compile your corpus and execute what gets comp=
iled. This reveals bytecode opcodes not covered by the corpus. For example,=
 for Sui Move there were a few extremely rare opcodes related to pattern ma=
tching that were absent from 400k decompiled contracts and from the initial=
 corpus, but got covered later this way.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"identifier-renaming-=
with-tree-sitter">Identifier renaming with tree-sitter<a class=3D"hash-link=
" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Identifier renaming with tree-sitter" title=
=3D"Direct link to Identifier renaming with tree-sitter" href=3D"https://no=
warp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#identifier-renaming-with-tree-sitter">=
=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>A problem the fuzzer encounters when working with a generated corpus and=
 grammar-aware mutations is the rate of semantic errors. Mutations often sh=
uffle identifiers and code structure, producing lots of "undeclared variabl=
e" errors that do not let the fuzzer open new paths.</p>
<p>The solution: write a script that renames all identifiers to determinist=
ic names and saves the result to a separate renamed corpus. Here is <a href=
=3D"https://gist.github.com/jubnzv/10649e33865430d88de8eaa91fa50e9e" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">a 50-line script</a> doing this wit=
h <code>tree-sitter-solidity</code>.</p>
<p>The simplest approach that works: name all identifiers with a uniform pa=
ttern, e.g. <code>v0</code>, <code>v1</code>, ... Save this corpus and let =
<code>afl-ts</code> (in particular the <code>ts-bank</code> mutation) find =
the errors.</p>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-named-corpus-finding-e7d1ad10ebeba599f78f0a93f79b842a.png" style=3D"width=
: 70%;"></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em>Solidity: <code>ts-kdel</code> mutation on a rena=
med corpus =E2=86=92 ICE (<a href=3D"https://github.com/argotorg/solidity/i=
ssues/16636" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">solidity#16636</=
a>). Without renaming, this would only trigger an "undeclared variable" err=
or.</em></div>
<br>
<p>The approach is straightforward and a similar one is used in the generat=
ion routine of <a href=3D"https://github.com/softsec-kaist/codealchemist" t=
arget=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">CodeAlchemist</a> =E2=80=94 a =
program generator for fuzzing JavaScript engines <a href=3D"https://nowarp.=
io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#references">[4]</a> =E2=80=94 for the same =
purpose.</p>
<p>Additionally, you may want to seed stdlib identifiers or language keywor=
ds to challenge the semantic passes.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"dictionaries">Dictio=
naries<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Dictionaries" tit=
le=3D"Direct link to Dictionaries" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-=
testing-part-1#dictionaries">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>A fuzzing dictionary is a list of tokens that the fuzzer inserts into in=
puts during mutations. All three fuzzers support them: AFL++ via <a href=3D=
"https://aflplus.plus/docs/fuzzing_in_depth/#c-using-multiple-cores" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer"><code>-x</code></a>, honggfuzz via =
<code>--dict</code>, and libFuzzer via <code>-dict</code>. A custom diction=
ary for the language must be used if you run AFL++ without <code>AFL_CUSTOM=
_MUTATOR_ONLY =3D 1</code> =E2=80=94 this enables the havoc pass to add mea=
ningful constructions to the code.</p>
<p>Ideas for initial dictionary setup:</p>
<ul>
<li>Language's grammar or parser implementation</li>
<li>Common patterns from documentation and examples</li>
<li>Names of standard functions and language elements (e.g. possible modifi=
ers or values of <code>pragma</code>)</li>
<li><code>{</code>, <code>[</code> and similar symbols =E2=80=93 these ofte=
n give interesting results</li>
<li>Constructions involved in previous crashes (find in regression unit tes=
ts and/or GitHub search for previous ICEs)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://aflplus.plus/docs/env_variables/#5-settings-for-afl-=
clang-fast--afl-clang-fast-afl-clang-lto-afl-gcc-fast" target=3D"_blank" re=
l=3D"noopener noreferrer"><code>AFL_LLVM_DICT2FILE</code></a> =E2=80=94 aut=
o-extracts string comparisons from the target at compile time. Useful as a =
supplement, but for compiler fuzzing a hand-crafted dictionary from the lan=
guage grammar is more effective</li>
</ul>
<p>Focus on keeping entries atomic; avoid long constructions. For example, =
instead of <code>let a =3D &amp;mut x</code> add <code>&amp;mut</code> and =
<code>let</code> separately =E2=80=93 havoc and grammar-aware mutators will=
 figure it out by combining them with existing identifiers and operations.<=
/p>
<p>After running the corpus for a while, it is a good idea to:</p>
<ul>
<li>Check coverage =E2=80=93 typically you can find operators/constructions=
 that are hit most rarely =E2=80=93 add them to the dictionary</li>
<li>Include constructions from findings made by the fuzzer</li>
</ul>
<h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"triage-workflow">Tri=
age workflow<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Triage work=
flow" title=3D"Direct link to Triage workflow" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/bl=
og/compiler-testing-part-1#triage-workflow">=E2=80=8B</a></h2>
<p>The typical output of a fuzzer is a number of crash and hang (timeout) f=
iles =E2=80=94 usually big files with lots of irrelevant garbage. Additiona=
lly, some crashes are duplicated despite the AFL++ deduplication mechanism,=
 because the same bug may be caused by different syntactic constructions le=
ading to different triggering paths. The goal of triaging is to remove dupl=
icated crashes first, and then minimize the remaining files to a <a href=3D=
"https://stackoverflow.com/help/minimal-reproducible-example" target=3D"_bl=
ank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">minimal reproducible example</a> (MRE) to =
report.</p>
<p>The suggested approach:</p>
<ol>
<li><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#deduplication=
">Deduplicate</a> crashes with a triage script that analyzes the backtrace =
of crash/hang callsites</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#minimization"=
>Minimize</a> the results =E2=80=94 manually, using tooling, or with LLMs</=
li>
<li><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#report-filing=
">Report filing</a></li>
</ol>
<p>Each stage is described below.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"deduplication">Dedup=
lication<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Deduplication" =
title=3D"Direct link to Deduplication" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compi=
ler-testing-part-1#deduplication">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>A long campaign produces hundreds of crash files for a handful of underl=
ying bugs. Most of them are duplicates of the same panic triggered by diffe=
rent inputs, plus a tail of "benign" panics (stack overflows from parser bu=
gs, intentional TODO errors, etc.) that should not be reported. A short scr=
ipt handles the filtering and grouping.</p>
<p>The algorithm:</p>
<ol>
<li>Collect crash inputs from all AFL++ output dirs across workers</li>
<li>Replay each crash against the harness with backtrace enabled</li>
<li>Filter out benign panics by matching known patterns (unimplemented feat=
ures, stack overflows, etc.)</li>
<li>Extract the throw location from the backtrace</li>
<li>Normalize the panic message =E2=80=94 strip identifiers, source locatio=
ns, numbers, etc.</li>
<li>Group and cache crashes to avoid reporting old bugs again</li>
</ol>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-triage-script-085b3fef0e62ad93d40dd58ac164f67a.png" style=3D"width: 75%;"=
></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em><code>triage.py</code> output for the Solidity ca=
mpaign: 157 bugs considered unique by AFL grouped into 16 unique locations<=
/em></div>
<br>
<p>While the script seems easy to implement with LLMs, make sure it works c=
orrectly =E2=80=94 especially backtrace parsing and deduplication logic =E2=
=80=94 to avoid losing valid bugs.</p>
<p>An example implementation of such a script for a Solidity fuzzing campai=
gn is available as a <a href=3D"https://gist.github.com/jubnzv/827f06a16e21=
27c1bfed17de0c139619" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">gist</a=
>.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"minimization">Minimi=
zation<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Minimization" tit=
le=3D"Direct link to Minimization" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-=
testing-part-1#minimization">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>When minimizing a crash report manually, use the <a href=3D"https://www.=
debuggingbook.org/html/DeltaDebugger.html" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopene=
r noreferrer">delta debugging technique</a> =E2=80=94 a classic troubleshoo=
ting approach.</p>
<p>Among the tools, <a href=3D"https://github.com/uw-pluverse/perses" targe=
t=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">perses</a> and <a href=3D"https://=
github.com/langston-barrett/treereduce" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener n=
oreferrer">treereduce</a> can help =E2=80=94 both provide grammar-aware red=
uction. <code>afl-tmin</code> is not a good fit here, because it operates a=
t the bit/byte level and knows nothing about the grammar.</p>
<p>But typically it is not worth your time =E2=80=94 you can safely delegat=
e it to an LLM without any extra commands. Two things to watch for: tell th=
e model not to report ASTs recovered after parsing errors; on weird-looking=
 source, it sometimes gives up without reproducing the bug.</p>
<div align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://nowarp.io/assets/images/2026-04-1=
7-minimized-solidity-8fb5a04c742f497d216648fde05b56b4.png"></div>
<div align=3D"center"><em>Minimized by LLM: the original crash file and the=
 minimized version (<a href=3D"https://github.com/argotorg/solidity/issues/=
16622" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">solidity#16622</a>)</e=
m></div>
<br>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"report-filing">Repor=
t filing<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Report filing" =
title=3D"Direct link to Report filing" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compi=
ler-testing-part-1#report-filing">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>After deduplication and minimization, you need to check for duplicates a=
gainst existing issues and write a report.</p>
<p>LLMs work great here, but you need a good prompt:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ask the model to check for duplicates with <code>gh</code>.</li>
<li>Always ask it to reproduce with the real compiler, not with the fuzzing=
 harness.</li>
<li>Write very concise reports without root cause analysis or suggested fix=
es =E2=80=94 this avoids hallucinations. Don't write anything you did not c=
heck by yourself.</li>
</ul>
<p>First, triage a few reports by yourself, then write a CLAUDE.md triage g=
uide for the model to follow. The complete move-fuzz triage/minimization/re=
porting prompt <a href=3D"https://github.com/nowarp/move-fuzz/blob/f59321cb=
299c4877d64493d4c0a95d2f54f5f7bc/CLAUDE.md" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopen=
er noreferrer">is available</a> in the <code>move-fuzz</code> repo.</p>
