<p>The campaign was run on a 2019 Intel i7 U-series and did not take that m=
uch time. The goal was to verify the approach, not to find all possible bug=
s, because running the infrastructure takes resources. These findings were =
mostly the result of initial corpus generation and quality mutators, and re=
lied on coverage-guided path exploration much less.</p>
<p>Here is the concrete configuration used in fuzzing campaigns:</p>
<ul>
<li>Sui Move and Leo were fuzzed mostly with crafted MetaMut-style mutators=
 with additional afl-ts instances. Default AFL++ mutations with custom dict=
s were applied for some workers. honggfuzz and libfuzzer workers with dicts=
 were applied in 1 thread for some time.</li>
<li>Solidity and Solang both were fuzzed with <code>afl-ts</code> workers m=
ostly because solidity has a large corpus of contracts (e.g. <a href=3D"htt=
ps://huggingface.co/datasets/Zellic/all-ethereum-contracts" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Zellic dataset</a>, lots of regression tests=
 for previous findings in the Solidity repo) and good <a href=3D"https://gi=
thub.com/JoranHonig/tree-sitter-solidity" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener=
 noreferrer">up-to-date tree-sitter grammar</a>. Default AFL++ mutations wi=
th custom dicts were applied for some workers.</li>
<li>Cairo =E2=80=93 a MetaMut-style mutators with only mutations for rare c=
onstructions and <code>afl-ts</code>. AFL++ mutations were disabled =E2=80=
=93 since the fuzzing campaign there has extremely low stability and often =
hits memory limits because of <a href=3D"https://github.com/salsa-rs/salsa"=
 target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Salsa</a>, any extra executi=
ons are expensive because they clutter the corpus making the fuzzing less e=
ffective. Thus, only grammar-aware mutations were applied there.</li>
</ul>
<p>While most of the bugs were found for Sui Move, the approach is maybe mo=
re developed there =E2=80=94 Sui Move was used as the initial target for fu=
zzing, as a follow-up to <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/skry/" target=3D=
"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">previous work</a>, so the tooling was =
matured on it before being applied to the other compilers.</p>
<p>There is no precise statistics which custom mutators give the best resul=
ts nor comparision, while most finding were made by custom MetaMut-style mu=
tations and the <code>afl-ts</code> mutator. This is not a paper evaluating=
 a simple mutator =E2=80=93 if your goal is also to find bugs in production=
 code, you should use all the approaches giving you the result with low eff=
ort and proven result; combining multiple fuzzers for better corpus diversi=
ty and quickier path findng.</p>
<h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"challenges">Challeng=
es<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Direct link to Challenges" title=3D"=
Direct link to Challenges" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-=
part-1#challenges">=E2=80=8B</a></h3>
<p>Some challenges encountered during these campaigns:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Corpus growth with big files</strong> =E2=80=94 if you start wi=
thout a good initial corpus and enable <code>ts-add</code>, the corpus accu=
mulates oversized entries that slow down the whole campaign. Minimize early=
 and aggressively.</li>
<li><strong>Stability of stateful compilers</strong> =E2=80=94 Cairo uses <=
a href=3D"https://github.com/salsa-rs/salsa" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noope=
ner noreferrer">Salsa</a>, an incremental computation library. While conven=
ient for tooling development, it complicates fuzzing: the fuzzing state has=
 to be reset every N iterations to avoid OOM, and the MetaMut-style mutator=
 has to be tweaked accordingly. Move and Leo are mostly stable; any minor i=
ssues are likely caused by map type usage, but they don't affect the campai=
gn.</li>
<li><strong>Tree-sitter grammar quality</strong> =E2=80=94 the whole pipeli=
ne (corpus generation, <code>afl-ts</code>, renaming script) relies heavily=
 on the grammar parsing valid source without <code>ERROR</code> nodes. Whil=
e <code>afl-ts</code> tries to recover from <code>ERROR</code> nodes by ins=
erting syntactically valid code via its <code>ts-chaos</code> strategy, it =
is more efficient to run on a clean grammar.</li>
<li><strong>Reproducibility across versions</strong> =E2=80=94 compilers mo=
ve fast. An ICE found at HEAD may already be fixed by the time someone tria=
ges the report, or the minimizer may shift the behavior to a different inte=
rnal error. Pin the submodule version in the harness and include the exact =
commit in every report.</li>
</ul>
<h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"conclusion-and-furth=
er-work">Conclusion and further work<a class=3D"hash-link" aria-label=3D"Di=
rect link to Conclusion and further work" title=3D"Direct link to Conclusio=
n and further work" href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#=
conclusion-and-further-work">=E2=80=8B</a></h2>
<p>This blogpost shares experience setting up a cheap, fast fuzzing campaig=
n for a non-mainstream language to find ICE. The approach and tooling are r=
eproducible for any compiler.</p>
<p>Two new AFL++ grammar-aware mutators are introduced: <a href=3D"https://=
nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#afl-ts-tree-sitter-based-afl-mutator=
"><code>afl-ts</code></a> mutator that works with any tree-sitter grammar, =
and a <a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#metamut-sty=
le-mutators">MetaMut-style</a> LLM-generated mutator that produces hundreds=
 of language-specific operations from a few prompts. Both proved effective =
in finding ICE.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#corpus-and-dic=
tionaries">Corpus and dictionary setup</a> is covered with practical advice=
: collect broadly, minimize aggressively, mix manual dictionary entries wit=
h <code>AFL_LLVM_DICT2FILE</code> auto-generation. Helper tools (tsgen, val=
idation scripts) are included.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://nowarp.io/blog/compiler-testing-part-1#triage-workflo=
w">Minimization and triage</a> are LLM-assisted: a CLAUDE.md triage guide h=
andles bucketing and MRE generation, while <code>afl-cmin</code> and perses=
 (or an LLM directly) shrink test cases. Concise prompts without root cause=
 analysis reduce hallucination.</p>
<p>It is like experience sharing =E2=80=93 before digging into tools and li=
terature this setup took a couple of weeks; with the approach described her=
e, it takes 1-2 days to get real findings.</p>
<p>We intentionally don't consider approaches to testing that require more =
time and effort to implement. Oracles, miscompilation, and implementation/s=
pecification mismatch errors =E2=80=93 these techniques are out of scope an=
d will be described in the next part, since this post is already large as f=
uck.</p>
